  "text": "This article is organized as follows: I will first describe the ideas that underlie the model (quantum metabolism) that is invoked to derive the allometric relation given by Eq. [CITATION_1] . I will then apply this allometric law and analogous relations to predict that metabolic potential, estimated as the total amount of energy consumed per gram of body weight during the life span of the organism, is not a universal constant, as assumed in Pearl (9), but is highly dependent on factors such as taxonomic status and ecological constraints. This dependency, which is supported by empirical data, is shown to provide one of the strongest arguments against the rate of living theory. I will then describe the longevitystability hypothesis and invoke this condition to develop the stability theory of aging and its applications to the study of CR on life span. This study revolves around directionality theory. I will recall the basic tenets of this evolutionary model, and apply it to explain the large variability in life span observed in mammalian populations, and also to investigate the role of life history in determining the response of life span to CR. The article concludes with a commentary on empirical considerations-in particular an analysis of the quantitative response of life span to CR.",
